node.text: Eileen Mockus, CEO of sustainable homeware company @Coyuchi, talks with @archdigestpro editor @katy_magic about how to make your home more sustainable by making a few simple design choices.

node.title: In Conversation: Eileen Mockus, CEO of @coyuchi

node.accessibility_caption: Photo by Architectural Digest on July 31, 2021. May be an image of furniture and living room.

node.text:
In the living room of this home in upstate New York, the historical integrity was maintained by preserving the delicate plaster medallions that pepper the ceiling depicting Tudor roses with soft curling petals, as well as a heraldic crest and lion. Grander still is the formal dining room, where lively custom scenic wallpaper showing the Bedford Hills property in a fictional past time covers the walls. The clients had commissioned a hand-painted mural for a previous home, which #AD100 designer Sheila Bridges (@harlemtoilegirl) took inspiration from.

Explore the country estate at our bio link. Photo by @frankfrancesstudio; design by @harlemtoilegirl; styled by @mieketenhave; words by Camille Okhio.

node.accessibility_caption: Photo by Architectural Digest on July 31, 2021. May be an image of tree and nature.

node.text:
“[Architect Howard Backen] is like a great software designer, someone who approaches design as an accentuation of function,” says Ashton Kutcher (@aplusk), who has broad experience in technology start-ups. “A software designer wants to get people where they want to be with the fewest clicks. Howard wants to get you where you want to be with the fewest doors and obstacles. He also knows that there are certain places where you want a barrier to mark a threshold and create a little friction,” Kutcher adds.

Explore his home with Mila Kunis at our bio link. Photo by @douglasfriedman; styling by @michaelreynoldsnyc; design by @charlesandcostudio; architecture by @backengillamarchitects; words by @mayer.rus.

node.accessibility_caption: Photo by Architectural Digest on July 31, 2021. May be an image of furniture and living room.

node.text:
While most of the decor in this Coral Gables home is new, a set of vintage leather accent chairs is one notable exception. The family brought them with them to Connecticut and back to Florida again to be part of designer @jenniferbunsa's final composition.

Explore the bold and colorful home at our bio link. Photo by @nicole_franzen; design by @jenniferbunsa; words by @gabyulloa_.

node.accessibility_caption: Photo by Architectural Digest on July 30, 2021. May be an image of indoor.

node.text:
Musician @troyesivan on his home in Melbourne: “I was living in the States for about five years, longing to be in Australia, before the pandemic brought me home. As much as I’ve missed touring and seeing people, it’s been cool to be forced to stay still for a second. I wake up every day excited to make something new, in a house that tells the story of my life and the places I’ve loved."

Step into his incredible Victorian-era home at our bio link. Photo by @smartanson; styling by @joseph_gardner;  design by @flackstudio_; words by @mayer.rus.

node.accessibility_caption: Photo by Architectural Digest on July 30, 2021. May be an image of table, chandelier and living room.

node.text:
The walls of this Atherton home's dining room weren’t initially painted purple, but something inspired homeowner Brigette Lau to take the bold plunge. “Edel [Legaspi] knew what she was talking about,” says Lau of her home's designer, adding, “I’m excited to start entertaining inside again.” The @kellylambstudios God’s Eye Table is surrounded by @gubiofficial Beetle chairs upholstered in @knoll fabric and @hollyhuntdesign leather trim detail. Hanging from the ceiling is a Gabriel Scott Luna Three Tier Chandelier that shines against the aubergine wall color, which is Wine Stain by @dunnedwards.

Tour the color-filled home at our bio link. Photo by @rogerdaviesphotography; design by @legaspicourtsdesign; words by @zoesessums.

node.accessibility_caption: Photo by Architectural Digest on July 30, 2021. May be an image of furniture and living room.

node.text:
In many ways, designer @byronrisdon's bathroom cabinet, which has moved with him over the years, is a totem for his entire D.C. apartment, which swells with texture and history. And, it should be said, pragmatism: Throughout its 950 square feet, the designer has deftly integrated auction finds and upcycled items—some of them finding their way to Risdon from jobs for clients. The South Carolina native calls the two-bedroom flat a “well-thought-out hodgepodge,” but don’t be fooled: Risdon’s is an elevated, elegant interior that holds together its component parts like a perfectly baked apple crisp.

Tour his whole home at our bio link. Photo by @eastandlane; design by @byronrisdon; words by  Lila Allen.

node.accessibility_caption: Photo by Architectural Digest on July 29, 2021. May be an image of furniture and living room.

node.text:
"Supernatural" and "Gilmore Girls" alum @jaredpadalecki and wife @genpadalecki purchased their current Austin home in 2012, and have spent the years since slowly creating their ideal modern farmhouse. That’s where their three children (Thomas, 9, Shepherd, 7, and Odette, 4), as well as numerous dogs, chickens, mini horses, and even bees, live together in harmony. The house—which began as a model “Texas Tuscan,” according to their designer, Virginia Davidson (@v_d_i_d)—underwent a full gut renovation in order to become a compound inspired by the historic German homesteads of nearby Fredericksburg.

We're down in Austin, Texas, today visiting "Supernatural" star @jaredpadalecki and @genpadalecki as they take us through their cozy family home.

Watch the whole tour at our link in bio.

node.text:
“It feels period to start, and by the time you’re in the back, the house almost completely opens to the field,” homeowner David Ren says of the transition of his historic home in Hudson Valley.

Tour the renovated Victorian at our bio link. Photo by @matthewwilliamson; design by @workstead; styling by @mieketenhave; words by David Sokol.

node.accessibility_caption: Photo by Architectural Digest on July 28, 2021. May be an image of furniture and bedroom.

node.text:
“It was really a beautiful spot right at the end of a row of all the new construction…[overlooking] the mountain,” interior designer Roger Higgins (@rhigginsinteriors) recalls of this Montana home, which is located at the Yellowstone Club in Big Sky. His clients, the Gravettes, with three young sons and two French bulldogs, were specifically in need of ample room for entertaining, as well as cozy spaces for their close-knit clan. “They wanted this to be somewhere they could all go,” Higgins adds.

Tour the mountainside home at our bio link. Photo by @haris.kenjar; design by @rhigginsinteriors; words by @ericrallen.

node.accessibility_caption: Photo by Architectural Digest on July 28, 2021. May be an image of nature, tree and grass.

node.text:
Bill Caleo, cofounder of the @thebrooklynhomecompany, a boutique real estate–development firm, and Megan Noetzel LeFauve, an interior designer, envisioned their Catskills home as a year-round compound for themselves, their children, and their extended families. In addition to the three-bedroom house, the property includes a garage with a bunk room, a guest cottage, a playhouse, a pool, and a pool pavilion. There’s even a pond full of sunfish, shiners, and bass.

Tour the whole home at our bio link. Photo by Matthew Williams; design by @thebrooklynhomecompany and Megan Noetzel LeFauve; architecture by @langarchitecture; words by @stephen_wallis.

node.text:
“We felt like in New York we were getting the best of both cities in the gorgeous views,” designer @carolannblinken says, referring to the Manhattan location of her part-time residence. That home boasts breathtaking views across the Hudson River and into New Jersey. But as far as the eye may be able to see, Blinken has come even further when it comes to the creative process involved.

Tour the whole home at our bio link. Photo by @jeffholt; design by @carolannblinken; words by @christianelemieux.
